    "body" : "<p>In a GET request, the request parameters are taken from the query string (the data following the question mark on the URL). For example, the URL <a href=\"http://hostname.com?p1=v1&amp;p2=v2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://hostname.com?p1=v1&amp;p2=v2</a> contains two request parameters - - p1 and p2. In a POST request, the request parameters are taken from both query string and the posted data which is encoded in the body of the request.</p>\n\n<p>This example demonstrates how to include the value of a request parameter in the generated output:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Hello &lt;b&gt;&lt;%= request.getParameter(\"name\") %&gt;&lt;/b&gt;!\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If the page was accessed with the URL:</p>\n\n<pre><code>http://hostname.com/mywebapp/mypage.jsp?name=John+Smith\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>the resulting output would be:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Hello &lt;b&gt;John Smith&lt;/b&gt;!\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If name is not specified on the query string, the output would be:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Hello &lt;b&gt;null&lt;/b&gt;!\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This example uses the value of a query parameter in a scriptlet:</p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;%\n    if (request.getParameter(\"name\") == null) {\n        out.println(\"Please enter your name.\");\n    } else {\n        out.println(\"Hello &lt;b&gt;\"+request. getParameter(\"name\")+\"&lt;/b&gt;!\");\n    }\n%&gt;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
